comment: yeah, any driving job will quickly expose weaknesses
got an uncle that's a courier, he just buys $3000 cars and runs em into the ground
like they probably come with 80000 or 100000 miles he just has a mechanic patch em together for like another 50000 miles or something
My Focus came with 93k or so miles, currently at 103k
It's a '14, so it *should* last at least until 200k, hopefully
But the bigger issue is that there's a design flaw with the dual-clutch automatic transmission.  It's a big enough deal that there were court cases and such.
yeah, all brands/models have an achellies heel
In this one, it's increased wear and tear and potential failure to deliver power
some have a really lousy designed water pump buried under the engine so engine gotta come out to replace it
When I first got this car, we got the transmission repaired within the first month while the dealer was covering half the costs
and water pumps are a common thing to go in high milage cars
some I heard are driven on the TIMING belt
The problem that prompted it was that sometimes the clutch wouldn't properly engage, so I'd hit the gas but power wouldn't be delivered until a second or two later.
so like to service them the engine has to come apart
It's one of the downsides of cars becoming more compact

Older cars used to be much spacier.  And the lower-tech mechanical nature meant anyone could work on them if they had knowledge.  And you didn't have to disassemble the entire engine compartment to fix one small issue.
yeah some new cars with 8-9 speed traditional transmissions like to lurch/kick at near stop
it's one of those dumb design gaffs
That's what my car does sometimes.  It's more of an issue on hills, but essentially it can't decide whether or not it wants to deliver power
My RPMs will be steady, but the car keeps switching between power on and power off.  Makes the climb very jerky
yeah, it seems like they made things more complex and have a hard time packing the complexity into a small space
cuz I imagine 9 gears in a transmission gets crowded
I guess it shouldn't be too surprising.  This thing is a 6-speed automatic xD
yeah esp in a focus sized car
But hot damn is that mileage sexy~
I averaged somewhere between 27 and 28 mpg my first day doing deliveries
I was hitting long stretches of road with no stop signs or red lights
that's why CVTs were probably invented
Sadly, car companies don't have the balls to treat them like CVT's :|
The entire point of the CVT design is to achieve the optimal gear ratio depending on speed / rpm
it's like two cones that just sorta slide around with a band/belt between them
But people are weirded out by that so they make them behave like they have a standard gear assembly.  Completely defeating the purpose!
Man, if people don't like CVT's, they gonna hate it when EVs take over xD
if there's "steps", you're missing out on the in-between adjustments too
yeah I think it's just because naturally or by habit people expect a shift to happen
so you just sit there pressing the gas like
Your most fuel efficient gear is generally gonna be one of the highway speed gears, and near the lowest maintainable rpm possible.
